1290","Sussex, England":"Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Papilon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and English: from Old French <i>papillon</i> (from Latin <i>papilio</i>), Middle English <i>papillioun</i> ‘butterfly’, perhaps used as a nickname for a flighty individual.","Haitian: from the personal name or nickname <i>Papillon</i>, which has the same meaning as 1 above.","History: The surname <i>Papillon</i> of French origin is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America."],"variants":[{"name":"Papillion","meanings":["French: variant of   Papillon   ‘butterfly’."]}]},{"name":"Johanna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Johannah","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Johannes</i> (  see  John  )."]},{"name":"Jonna","meanings":["contracted form of   Johanna ."]},{"name":"Jane","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":10,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705191,"age":35,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":48,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":102,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Johanna De Papilon was born in 1280, in Sussex, England, her father, William De Papilon, was 40 and her mother, Mrs de Papilon, was 14. She married Walter De Woknolle in 1321, in Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1280–":"1280–Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1288–Male":"1288–Surnud","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1267–Female":"1267–Surnud","1315":"1315","1300":"1300","1267":"1267","1321":"1321","1288":"1288","1240":"1240","1382":"1382","1280":"1280","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1280–":"1280–Kuollut","1280–Female":"1280–Kuollut","1288–Male":"1288–Kuollut","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1267–Female":"1267–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1300":"1300","1267":"1267","1321":"1321","1288":"1288","1240":"1240","1382":"1382","1280":"1280","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1280–":"1280–Décédée","1280–Female":"1280–Décédée","1288–Male":"1288–Décédé","1300–Female":"1300–Décédée","1240–Male":"1240–Décédé","1267–Female":"1267–Décédée","1315":"1315","1300":"1300","1267":"1267","1321":"1321","1288":"1288","1240":"1240","1382":"1382","1280":"1280","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","Sussex, England":"Sussex, Angle